Alright, putting on my lead UI designer hat. I’m going to be direct and specific. This is genuinely good work, but here’s where I’d push back in a design review:

Visby Quest — UI Design Review

🟢 What’s Exceptional First
Before critique, credit where it’s due. Google’s research found that users prefer design that makes them feel something, rather than emotionless, purely pragmatic interfaces ￼ — and this app absolutely delivers on that. The dark wood textures, aged parchment cards, gold typography and Balle Bagge create a cohesive emotional world that most tourism apps completely fail at. That’s genuinely hard to achieve and you’ve nailed it.

🔴 Issue 1 — Typography Inconsistency (High Priority)
Looking across the screens, you’re mixing at least 3 different font styles:
	∙	The medieval serif on the landing page headline (“Skattjakt genom Visbys gränder”)
	∙	A clean modern sans-serif for body text
	∙	A third mid-weight style in the UI cards
Consistent UI design helps users develop mental models for how your app works — consistency is achieved with things like using one color palette, the same typography, or uniform spacing throughout. ￼
The medieval headline font is beautiful but it only appears on the landing page. It should be used more deliberately and consistently — for all major headings — to reinforce the theme throughout. Right now the app switches personality between screens.
Fix: Define 3 type roles — Display (medieval serif), Heading (gold serif), Body (cream sans-serif) — and stick to them rigidly.

🔴 Issue 2 — Touch Target Sizes (High Priority)
Looking at the bottom navigation bar — “Hem”, “Karta”, “Mitt Pussel”, “Skanna QR” — the icons and labels are quite small and tightly packed. Research confirms that even small interface adjustments measurably improve user trust, and proper touch target sizing is a core principle. ￼
Apple’s own Human Interface Guidelines recommend a minimum touch target of 44x44 points. Your bottom nav looks like it’s hitting around 36px. This is especially problematic because:
	∙	Your users are walking around cobblestone streets — one-handed, possibly in cold weather with gloves
	∙	They’re likely distracted and excited — precision tapping is harder
	∙	Older tourists, a key demographic, often have lower fine motor accuracy
Fix: Increase the bottom nav height by about 12–15px and give each icon more padding.

🟡 Issue 3 — Visual Hierarchy on the Map Screen (Medium Priority)
On the “Skattens rutt” / map screen, there are three competing visual zones fighting for attention simultaneously:
	1.	The “Uppdragskarta / 0/8 Samlade sigill” header card
	2.	The “Aktuellt mål: Kruttornet” card
	3.	The historical map itself
Figma’s design principle guidance says designers use hierarchy to help users recognize key information and distinguish less important elements at a glance — the strategic use of contrasting colors and spacing directs users to key elements. ￼
Right now everything feels equally weighted. The user’s one job on this screen is to navigate to the next QR location — but that goal doesn’t visually dominate.
Fix: Make the “Aktuellt mål” card the clear visual hero. Reduce the prominence of the progress tracker — move it to a subtle top bar rather than a large card.

🟡 Issue 4 — The Empty Puzzle State (Medium Priority)
The empty 0/15 puzzle is visually dead — a blank cream grid on a wood background. This is your biggest motivation problem. Each screen should focus on encouraging users to take one action — use consistent elements throughout your app to make it easy for users to know what to do. ￼
The empty state is a missed opportunity. When a user first sees an empty puzzle, their reaction should be excitement — “I want to fill this!” — not blankness.
Fix options:
	∙	Show a very blurred/dark silhouette of the final image as a teaser
	∙	Add a small Balle Bagge animation pointing at it saying something like “Scan your first QR to begin!”
	∙	Add subtle shimmer or glow on piece #1 to invite the first action

🟡 Issue 5 — The QR Scanner Screen Dark Theme Break (Medium Priority)
Every other screen uses warm parchment and brown tones. The QR scanner switches to a near-black dark UI — it’s jarring and breaks the medieval immersion completely. It suddenly feels like a generic modern app.
Design consistency is a cornerstone principle — visual elements like buttons, labels, and fonts should maintain a uniform style throughout your app so users can recognize and understand how to interact with it quickly. ￼
I understand the dark background is probably functional for the camera viewport — but the surrounding UI chrome doesn’t need to be dark.
Fix: Keep the camera viewfinder dark, but frame it with warm parchment UI — like a wooden “viewing window” frame around the camera. The STATUS and TIPS cards below could remain in the warm parchment style.

🟡 Issue 6 — No Loading / Transition Feedback (Medium Priority)
I can’t verify this from screenshots, but it’s worth flagging. Animations and clear transitions between screens are key bits of feedback that create a more satisfying user experience. ￼
When a QR code is successfully scanned, what happens? Is there a satisfying animation — a puzzle piece flying into place, a wax seal breaking, a scroll unfurling? This moment of delight is critical and often underdone.
Fix: That QR scan success moment deserves your best animation. A puzzle piece dramatically snapping into position with a satisfying sound could be the most memorable moment in the entire experience.

🟢 Issue 7 — Accessibility (Lower Priority but Important for Municipality Pitch)
If you’re pitching to Region Gotland, accessibility will come up. In 2024 there’s a significant push towards inclusive and accessible app designs — including screen reader compatibility and adaptability to various accessibility settings — such practices ensure compliance with global accessibility standards. ￼
The gold-on-dark-brown text on several screens may not meet WCAG AA contrast ratios (4.5:1 minimum). The gold-on-parchment is probably fine, but the gold labels on the dark map header card (“UPPDRAGSKARTA”, “SAMLADE SIGILL”) are worth checking.
Fix: Run your colour combinations through a contrast checker like Coolors or WebAIM before the pitch.

